as]]\n[[Category:Baseball teams established in 1961]]\n[[Category:1961 establishments in Texas]]\n[[Category:Companies that filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy in 2010]]\n[[Category:Sports in Arlington, Texas]]\n", "name_user": "Stjeanp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRangers Baseball Express, LLC:added missing 'million'", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Texas_Rangers_(baseball)"}
{"title_page": "RuPaul", "text_new": "{{pp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American actor, musician, and drag queen}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = RuPaul\n| image              = RuPaul at Dragcon by dvsross (cropped).jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = RuPaul at [[RuPaul's DragCon LA|DragCon LA]] in 2019\n| birth_name         = RuPaul Andre Charles\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1960|11|17}}\n| birth_place        = [[San Diego, California]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{hlist|[[Drag queen|Drag performer]]|actor|model|singer|songwriter|television personality|author}}\n| television         = ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]]''\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Georges LeBar|2017}}\n| website            = {{URL|rupaul.com}}\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist\n| embed = yes\n| background     = solo_singer\n| origin         = [[Atlanta, Georgia]], U.S.\n| genre          = {{hlist|[[Dance-pop]]|[[Dance music|dance]]|[[disco house]]|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[eurodance]]|[[electro house]]}}\n| label           = {{hlist|Funtone|Every|[[Tommy Boy Records|Tommy Boy]]|[[Rhino Entertainment|Rhino]]|RuCo|[[World of Wonder (production company)|World of Wonder]]}}\n| associated_acts = {{hlist|[[Lady Bunny]]|[[Michelle Visage]]}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''RuPaul Andre Charles''' (born November 17, 1960) is an American [[drag queen]], actor, model, singer, songwriter, and television personality.  Since 2009, he has produced and hosted the reality competition series ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]]'', for which he has received six [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Host for a Reality or Competition Program|Primetime Emmy Award]]s, in 2016, 2017, 2018, and 2019. RuPaul is considered to be the most commercially successful drag queen in the United States. In 2017, he was included in the annual [[Time 100|''Time'' 100]] list of the most influential people in the world.<ref name=\"time\" /> In 2019, ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' noted RuPaul as \"easily the world's most famous\" drag queen.<ref name=\"klein1\">{{cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2019/09/24/rupaul-drag-race-uk-dragcon/|title=As \u2018RuPaul\u2019s Drag Race\u2019 Expands to the U.K., DragCon Shines Light on Its Mainstream Success|last=Klein|first=Jessica|date=September 24, 2019|website=[[Fortune (magazine)]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nRuPaul was born and raised in [[San Diego, California]] and later moved to [[Atlanta, Georgia]] to study performing arts. He settled in [[LGBT culture in New York City|New York City]], where he became a popular fixture on the nightclub scene. RuPaul achieved international fame as a drag queen with the release of his debut single, \"[[Supermodel (You Better Work)]]\", which was included on his debut studio album ''[[Supermodel of the World]]'' (1993). In 1994, he became a spokesperson for [[MAC Cosmetics]], raising money for the [[Mac AIDS Fund]] and becoming the first drag queen to land a major cosmetics campaign. That year, he received his own talk show on [[VH1]], ''[[The RuPaul Show]]'', which he hosted for over 100 episodes, while co-hosting the morning radio show on [[WKTU]] with [[Michelle Visage]]. He has had continued success as a recording artist, releasing 14 studio albums to date (as of 2017), including ''[[Foxy Lady (RuPaul album)|Foxy Lady]]'' (1996), ''[[Champion (RuPaul album)|Champion]]'' (2009), ''[[Glamazon (album)|Glamazon]]'' (2011), ''[[Born Naked]]'' (2014), and ''[[American (album)|American]]'' (2017).\n\nAs an actor, RuPaul has made appearances in films including ''[[Crooklyn]]'' (1994), ''[[The Brady Bunch Movie]]'' (1995), ''[[To Wong Foo, Thanks for Everything! Julie Newmar]]'' (1995), ''[[But I'm a Cheerleader]]'' (1999), ''[[Hurricane Bianca]]'' (2016), the [[Comedy Central]] series ''[[Broad City]]'' (2017), and the [[Netflix]] original programming ''[[Girlboss]]'' (2017) and ''[[Grace and Frankie]]'' (2019). He has also published three books: ''[[Lettin' It All Hang Out]]'' (1995), ''[[Workin' It! RuPaul's Guide to Life, Liberty, and the Pursuit of Style]]'' (2010), and ''[[GuRu (book)|GuRu]]'' (2018). Additionally, ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' has produced eleven seasons to date (as of 2019) and has inspired several spin-off series, including ''[[RuPaul's Drag U]]'' and ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race All Stars]]''. He is also featured as a host on series such as ''[[Skin Wars]]'', ''[[Good Work (talk show)|Good Work]]'', and ''[[Gay for Play Game Show Starring RuPaul]]''. In June 2019, his daytime talk show ''[[RuPaul (talk show)|RuPaul]]'' premiered, which was cancelled after a three-week test run.<ref name=\"hollywoodrep\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/rupaul-daytime-talk-show-not-moving-at-fox-stations-1266055|title=RuPaul Daytime Talk Show Not Moving Ahead at Fox Stations|date=January 2, 2020|access-date=January 6, 2020|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|last=Porter|first=Rick}}</ref>\n\nRuPaul is indifferent to [[gender-specific pronoun]]s about him, writing: \"You can call me he. You can call me she. You can call me [[Live with Kelly and Ryan|Regis and Kathie Lee]]; I don't care! Just as long as you call me.\"<ref name=\"Autobiography\">{{cite book|author=RuPaul|title=Lettin' It All Hang Out: An Autobiography|publisher=[[Hachette Books|Hyperion Books]]|date=1995|isbn=978-0-7868-6156-9|url=https://archive.org/details/lettinitallhango00rupa}}</ref> RuPaul has also played male roles and makes public appearances in male and female drag.<ref name=\"Autobiography\" />\n\n==Early life==\nRuPaul was born in [[San Diego]], [[California]], on November 17, 1960.<ref name=\"glbtq\">{{cite web | title = RuPaul (RuPaul Andre Charles) | work = GLBTQ: An Encyclopedia of Gay, Lesbian, Bisexual, Transgender, and Queer Culture | publisher = GLBTQ, Inc. | date = August 16, 2005| first=Tina |last=Gianoulis | url = http://www.glbtqarchive.com/arts/rupaul_A.pdf | accessdate = March 24, 2009|archivedate=January 12, 2017|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170112134716/http://glbtqarchive.com/arts/rupaul_A.pdf | url-status=live}}</ref> He was named by his mother, Ernestine \"Toni\" Charles, a [[Louisiana]] native; the ''Ru'' came from [[roux]], which is the term for the base of [[gumbo]] and other [[Creole peoples|creole]] stews and soups.<ref>The Bonnie Hunt Show March 12, 2010</ref> When his parents divorced in 1967, he and his three sisters lived with their mother.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spin.com/2013/04/rupaul-runs-the-world-drag-race-supermodel/|title=RuPaul Runs The World |work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |date=April 1, 2013|first=Julianne Escobedo|last= Shepherd|accessdate= March 10, 2017| archivedate=February 14, 2017 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170214023747/http://www.spin.com/2013/04/rupaul-runs-the-world-drag-race-supermodel/ |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAt the age of 15, he moved to [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], with his sister Renetta to study [[performing arts]]. In the ensuing years, RuPaul struggled as a musician and filmmaker during the 1980s, where he worked at Atlanta's famed [[Plaza Theatre (Atlanta)|Plaza Theatre]]. In 1982, he debuted on an Atlanta [[Public-access television|public access]] [[variety show]] called ''[[The American Music Show]],'' in which he made frequent appearances over the years.<ref name=\"Autobiography\"/>{{rp|59}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://findingaids.library.emory.edu/documents/americanmusicshow1256/|title=American Music Show (Television show) video recordings, 1981\u20132005|date=May 17, 2013|website=findingaids.library.emory.edu|access-date=December 11, 2018}}</ref> He also participated in underground [[film|cinema]], helping create the low-budget film ''[[RuPaul Is: Starbooty!|Star Booty]]'', and an album by the same name. In Atlanta, RuPaul often performed at the Celebrity Club, managed by [[Larry Tee]], as a bar dancer or with his band, Wee Wee Pole.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G2-2871900054.html |title=Rupaul 1960\u2013 |publisher=Encyclopedia.com ([[Thomson Gale]]) |first=Ellen Dennis |last=French |date=2005 |accessdate=April 24, 2012 |archivedate=January 23, 2013 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130123123203/http://www.encyclopedia.com/topic/RuPaul.aspx%231-1G2:2871900054-full |url-status=live |df= }} Additional [https://web.archive.org/web/20170429084235/http://www.encyclopedia.com/people/literature-and-arts/music-popular-and-jazz-biographies/rupaul WebCitation archive] on March 10, 2017.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://bittersoutherner.com/southern-belles-latchkey-kids-and-thrift-store-crossdressers |title=Southern Belles, Latchkey Kids and Thrift-Store Crossdressers |last1=Warren |first1=Robert Burke |publisher=BitterSoutherner.com |accessdate=December 6, 2013| archivedate= June 23, 2016| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160623215100/http://bittersoutherner.com/southern-belles-latchkey-kids-and-thrift-store-crossdressers/#.WMLqGBIrIcg | url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Nelson|first=Sullivan|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8qHKpF3dYv0&t=6m15s |title=Going to Red Zone |quote=RuPaul, Lahoma and Larry Tee went to Red Zone to perform their disco act La Palace de Beaute. This video includes fabulous backup dancing by RuPaul and Lahoma.}}</ref> RuPaul also performed as a backup singer to [[Glen Meadmore]] along with drag queen [[Vaginal Davis]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Kot|first=Greg|title=What a Drag |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1995-09-01/entertainment/9509010298_1_new-york-dolls-angela-davis-glam|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=March 12, 2013|date=September 1, 1995| archivedate= April 24, 2016| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160424161541/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1995-09-01/entertainment/9509010298_1_new-york-dolls-angela-davis-glam| url-status=live}}</ref> RuPaul's first prominent national exposure came in 1989 dancing as an [[Extra (acting)|extra]] in the video for \"[[Love Shack]]\" by [[The B-52's]].{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n\nIn the early 1990s, RuPaul worked the Georgia club scene and was known by his full birth name. Initially participating in [[gender bender]]-style performances, RuPaul performed solo and in collaboration with other bands at several [[New York City]] nightclubs, most notably the [[Pyramid Club (New York)|Pyramid Club]]. He played opposite New York City drag performer Mona Foote (Nashom Benjamin) in the one-act [[science-fiction]] parody \"My Pet Homo\" written and directed by Jon Michael Johnson for Cooper Square Productions. He appeared for many years at the annual [[Wigstock]] [[Drag (clothing)|drag]] festival and appeared in the [[documentary film|documentary]] ''[[Wigstock: The Movie]]''. In the 1990s, RuPaul was known in the UK for his appearances on the [[Channel 4]] series ''Manhattan Cable'', a weekly series produced by [[World of Wonder (production company)|World of Wonder]] and presented by American Laurie Pike about New York's wild and wacky [[public-access television]] system.\n\n==Career==\n===1993\u20131997: ''Supermodel of the World'', ''Foxy Lady'', and ''Ho Ho Ho''===\nIn 1993, RuPaul recorded the [[Dance music|dance]]/[[house music|house]] album ''[[Supermodel of the World]]''. It was released through the rap label [[Tommy Boy Entertainment|Tommy Boy]], spawning the [[Dance music|dance track]] hit \"[[Supermodel (You Better Work)]]\". The [[music video]] was an unexpected success on MTV channels, as [[grunge]] and [[gangsta rap]] were popular at the time. The song peaked at 45 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. It charted on the [[UK Singles Chart]], peaking on the top 40 at 39. The song found the most success on the ''Billboard'' [[Hot Dance Club Songs|Hot Dance Music/Club Play]] chart, where it peaked at 2. Radio airplay, heavy rotation of the music video on [[MTV]] and television appearances on popular programs like ''[[The Arsenio Hall Show]]'' popularized the song.\n\n{{Rquote|right|What other people think of me is not my business. What I do is what I do. How people see me doesn't change what I decide to do. I don't choose projects so people don't see me as one thing or another. I choose projects that excite me. I think the problem is that people refuse to understand what drag is outside of their own belief system.|RuPaul<ref name=DS/>}}\n\nHis next two singles/videos, \"[[Back to My Roots]]\" and \"[[A Shade Shady (Now Prance)]]\", both went to the top spot on the ''Billboard'' Hot Dance Music/Club Play chart and furthered his [[Camp (style)|campy]] persona. Between them, \"[[House of Love (RuPaul song)|House of Love]]\" was released without a video. It failed to place on any U.S. charts, despite rising to 68 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].\n\nRuPaul was signed to a modeling contract for [[Make-up Art Cosmetics|MAC Cosmetics]]. Various billboards featured him in full drag, often with the text \"I am the MAC girl\". He also released his [[autobiography]], ''[[Lettin' It All Hang Out]]''. He promoted the book in part with a 1995 guest appearance on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''[[All My Children]]'', in a storyline that put it on the set of [[Erica Kane]]'s talk show \"The Cutting Edge\".\n\nThe next year he landed a talk show of his own on [[VH1]], called ''[[The RuPaul Show]]'', interviewing [[celebrity]] guests and musical acts. [[Diana Ross]], [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], [[Duran Duran]], [[Pat Benatar]], [[Mary J. Blige]], [[Bea Arthur]], [[Dionne Warwick]], [[Cyndi Lauper]], [[Olivia Newton-John]], [[Beenie Man]], [[Pete Burns]], [[Bow Wow Wow]], and the [[Backstreet Boys]] were notable guests. His co-host was [[Michelle Visage]], with whom he also co-hosted on [[WKTU]] radio. On one episode, RuPaul featured guests [[Chi Chi LaRue]] and [[Tom Chase]] speaking about the [[gay]] [[pornography|porn]] industry.\n\nLater in the year he released his second album, ''[[Foxy Lady (RuPaul album)|Foxy Lady]]'', this time on the L.A.-based [[Rhino Records]] label. Despite his growing celebrity, he failed to chart on the ''Billboard'' 200. However, the first single \"[[Snapshot (song)|Snapshot]]\" found success in the dance market and went to number four on the [[Hot Dance Club Songs|Hot Dance Music/Club Play]] chart. It also enjoyed limited mainstream success, charting at 95 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, which was his second and only other Hot 100 entry to date (1996?). The second single \"[[A Little Bit of Love (RuPaul song)|A Little Bit of Love]]\" only charted at 28 on the Hot Dance Music/Club Play chart. The album featured covers of a 1981 [[Diana Ross]] song \"Work That Body\", co-written by [[Paul Jabara]] and \"[[If You Were a Woman (And I Was a Man)|If You Were a Woman and I Was a Man]]\", originally recorded by [[Bonnie Tyler]]. Because of his strong fan base within the [[gay community]], RuPaul has performed at [[gay pride]] events and numerous [[gay club]]s. During this time RuPaul helped launch the return of WKTU radio in [[New York City]] and would serve as host of the morning show until 1998.\n\nIn 1997, he released his third album, a [[Christmas]] album entitled ''[[Ho Ho Ho (album)|Ho Ho Ho]]''. He has had guest appearances in many films, including both [[The Brady Bunch Movie|''Brady Bunch'' movies]], in which he played Jan's female guidance counselor. In 1997 RuPaul teamed with [[Martha Wash]] to remake the classic disco anthem, \"[[It's Raining Men]]\". The song was included on the 1998 compilation CD ''[[Rupaul's Go-Go Box Classics|RuPaul's Go Go Box Classics]]'', which was a collection of some of his favorite dance songs by other artists; this would be his third and final release through [[Rhino Records]] and a major record label. It was during this time that he appeared in [[Webex]] TV commercials and magazine ads. In 2002 he recorded with [[Brigitte Nielsen]], credited as Gitta, the [[Eurodance]] track \"You're No Lady\".\n\n===2004\u20132007: ''Red Hot'', ''ReWorked'', and ''Starrbooty''===\n[[File:RuPaul by David Shankbone.jpg|thumb|RuPaul in 2007]]\nIn 2004, RuPaul released his fourth album, ''[[Red Hot (album)|Red Hot]]'' on his own RuCo Inc. music label. It received some dance radio and club play, but very little press coverage. On his [[blog]], RuPaul discussed how he felt betrayed by the entertainment industry, particularly the [[gay press]]. In one incident, it was noted that ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' refused to review the album, instead asking him to make a comedic contribution to a fashion article. He likened the experience to \"a black person being invited to a party, but only if they'll serve.\" Despite his apparent dissatisfaction with the release, ''Red Hot'' showed RuPaul returning to the top of the dance charts in the US with the lead off single \"[[Looking Good, Feeling Gorgeous]]\" hitting number two on the dance chart. The second, \"[[Workout (RuPaul song)|WorkOut]]\", peaked at number five. The third and final single from the album \"People Are People\" a duet with Tom Trujillo peaked at number 10. The album itself only charted on the [[Dance/Electronic Albums|Top Electronic Albums]] chart, where it hit number nine.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2004-10-16/dance-electronic-albums |title=Dance/Electronic Albums : Oct 16, 2004 &#124; Billboard Chart Archive |magazine=Billboard.com |accessdate=December 3, 2013}}</ref> When asked about this in an interview, RuPaul said, \"Well, betrayed might be the wrong word. 'Betrayed' alludes to an idea that there was some kind of a promise made to me, and there never was. More so, I was disappointed. I don't feel like it was a betrayal. Nobody promises anything in show business and you understand that from day one. But, I don't know what happened. It seemed I couldn't get press on my album unless I was willing to play into the role that the mainstream press has assigned to gay people, which is as servants of straight ideals.\"<ref name=DS>RuPaul in Shankbone, David. [[n:RuPaul speaks about society and the state of drag as performance art|Interview with RuPaul]], [[Wikinews]], October 6, 2007.</ref>\n\n{{Wikinews|RuPaul speaks about society and the state of drag as performance art}}\nOn June 13, 2006, RuPaul released ''ReWorked'', his first [[remix]] album and fifth album overall. It features reworked versions of songs from his back catalog, as well as new recordings. The only single released from the album is a re-recording of \"Supermodel (You Better Work)\", reaching number 21 on the U.S. dance chart. June 20, 2007, saw the release of ''[[Starrbooty: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|Starrbooty (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)]]'' in the United States. The single \"Call Me Starrbooty\" was digitally released in 2007. The album contains new tracks as well as interludes with dialogue from the movie. The film was released on DVD in October 2007.\n\n===2008\u20132010: ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' and ''Champion''===\n[[File:Rupaul-2009 (cropped to shoulders).jpg|158px|left|thumb|RuPaul in March 2009.]]\nIn mid-2008, RuPaul began producing ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]]'', a [[reality television]] [[game show]] which aired on [[Logo (TV channel)|Logo]] in February 2009. The premise of the program has drag queens compete to be selected by RuPaul and a panel of judges as \"America's next drag superstar\". The first season's winner was [[BeBe Zahara Benet]], and first runner-up [[Nina Flowers]] was chosen by fans as \"Miss Congeniality\" through voting via the show's official website. In publicity preparation for the new show, RuPaul made appearances as a guest on several other shows in 2008 including as a guest judge on episode 6 of season 5 of ''[[Project Runway]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bravotv.com/project-runway/season-5/good-queen-fun |title=Project Runway Season 5 Good Queen Fun &#124; Bravo TV Official Site |publisher=Bravotv.com |date= |accessdate=December 3, 2013}}</ref> and as a guest \"chef\" on ''[[Paula's Party]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foodnetwork.com/paulas-party/diva-party/index.html |title=Diva Party : Paula's Party |publisher=Food Network |date= |accessdate=December 3, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131207232821/http://www.foodnetwork.com/paulas-party/diva-party/index.html |archivedate=December 7, 2013 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2009, RuPaul released the album ''[[Champion (RuPaul album)|Champion]]''. The album spawned four singles \"[[Cover Girl (RuPaul song)|Cover Girl]]\", \"[[Jealous of My Boogie]]\", \"[[Devil Made Me Do It]]\" and \"[[Tranny Chaser (song)|Tranny Chaser]]\". The album peaked at number 12 on the ''Billboard'' [[Dance/Electronic Albums]] as well as 26 on the ''Billboard'' [[Top Heatseekers]] chart. Logo's second annual [[NewNowNext Awards]] in 2009 were hosted by RuPaul. There he performed \"Jealous of My Boogie (Gomi & RasJek Edit)\". In March 2010, RuPaul released his second remix album, ''Drag Race'', the album features remixes of songs from the 2009 album ''Champion''.<ref>{{Citation|title=Drag Race by RuPaul|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/drag-race/361093827|language=en-us|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web |title=RuPaul Releases Drag Race Album |url=http://www.newnownext.com/rupaul-releases-drag-race-album/03/2010/ |publisher=[[NewNowNext]] |accessdate=30 March 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5rQQu6qKi?url=http://www.newnownext.com/rupaul-releases-drag-race-album/03/2010/ |archivedate=2010-07-23 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===2011\u20132013: ''Glamazon'', make-up and perfume line===\n\nIn April 2011, coinciding with the finale of season 3 of ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]]'', RuPaul released his sixth studio album ''[[Glamazon (album)|Glamazon]]'', produced by [[Revolucian]], who previously worked with RuPaul on his album ''Champion''. The album charted on ''Billboard\u2019s'' [[Dance/Electronic Albums]] and the ''Billboard'' [[Top Heatseekers]] chart at 11 and 8 respectively. In July 2011, RuPaul released another remix EP entitled ''SuperGlam DQ'', which features remixes of tracks from ''Glamazon'', remixes of the \"''Drag U'' Theme Song\", and a new song, \"Sexy Drag Queen\". Starting in June 2011, the second season of ''[[RuPaul's Drag U]]'' aired. In late 2011, promotions for [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 4)|season 4]] of ''Drag Race'' began. RuPaul made appearances on ''[[The Rosie Show]]'' and ''[[The Chew]]'', and also attended a ''Drag Race'' NY Premiere party at [[Patricia Field]]'s store in New York. Season 4 of ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]]'' premiered on [[Logo (TV channel)|Logo]] on January 30, 2012, with RuPaul returning as the main host and judge. After season 4 ended, [[TV.com]] declared it was the best reality TV show on television.\n\nIn the fall of 2012, the spin-off ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race All Stars (season 1)|RuPaul's Drag Race All Stars]]'' premiered after a large fan demand. The show featured past contestants of the previous four seasons to compete. Season 5 of ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]]'' premiered on January 28, 2013, with a 90-minute special and RuPaul returning as the main host and judge. On April 30, 2013, RuPaul released a single \"[[Lick It Lollipop]]\" featuring [[Lady Bunny]], who RuPaul previously collaborated with on ''Champion''. On October 25, 2013 RuPaul reported via Twitter that the new album would be released in January 2014.\n\nIn fall of 2013, RuPaul joined forces with cosmetic manufacturers Colorevolution to launch his debut make-up line featuring ultra-rich [[pigment]] cosmetics and a beauty collection. Released alongside the line was a [[unisex]] perfume entitled \"[[Glamazon by Colorevolution|Glamazon]]\". Talking to [[World of Wonder (production company)|World of Wonder]], RuPaul said: \"Glamazon is for women and men of all ages and preferences who share one thing in common: They are not afraid to be fierce. For me, glamour should be accessible to all, and I am committed to helping the world look and smell more beautiful.\" The line was exclusively sold on the Colorevolution website in various gift sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldofwonder.net/rupauls-glamazon-limited-edition-makeup-fragrance/ |title=RuPaul's \"Glamazon\" Limited Edition Makeup and Fragrance Available Now! |publisher=World of Wonder |date=November 12, 2013 |accessdate=December 3, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://colorevolution.com/category-Ru_Paul.html |title=Colorevolution Mineral Makeup&nbsp;\u2014 Ru Paul |publisher=Colorevolution.com |date= |accessdate=December 3, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131121053954/http://colorevolution.com/category-Ru_Paul.html |archivedate=November 21, 2013 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===2014: ''Born Naked'', ''What's The Tee?'', and ''Skin Wars''===\nRuPaul and [[Revolucian]] both confirmed through their [[Twitter]] and [[Instagram]] accounts that they had been working on an upcoming seventh studio album. ''[[Born Naked]]'' was released on February 24, 2014 to coincide with the premiere of the 6th season of ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 6)|RuPaul's Drag Race]]''. Prior to the premiere, an album of RuPaul cover songs performed by the Season 6 cast was released on January 28, 2014. The covers album is titled ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 6)#Soundtrack|RuPaul Presents The CoverGurlz]]'' and contains RuPaul songs from 2009\u20132013. To further promote the ''Drag Race'' season premiere, RuPaul, representing Logo TV (and parent company [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]) was chosen to ring the [[NASDAQ]] closing bell on February 24, 2014. The week of its release, ''Born Naked'' reached number one on the [[iTunes]] dance album chart. The following week it placed at number 4 on the US ''Billboard'' dance chart and 85 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart. In a profile by ''[[The New York Times]]'' it was revealed that RuPaul is currently working on a porcelain statuette of his likeness.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schulman|first=Michael|title=In Drag, It Turns Out, There Are Second Acts|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/23/fashion/RuPaul-Drag-Race-television.html?_r=1|accessdate=February 22, 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=February 21, 2014}}</ref> On April 9, 2014 RuPaul and [[Michelle Visage]] released the first episode of their podcast, ''[[RuPaul: What's The Tee?|RuPaul: What's the Tee? with Michelle Visage]]''. In August, he joined the reality competition show ''[[Skin Wars]]'' acting as a judge.\n\n===2015: ''Realness'', ''Good Work'', and ''Slay Belles''===\nOn March 2, 2015, RuPaul released his eighth studio album, ''[[Realness (RuPaul album)|Realness]]''. The release coincided with the premiere of the seventh season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race''. In April, he launched and began hosting a new show, ''[[Good Work (TV series)|Good Work]]'', a plastic surgery-themed talk show for [[E!]]. In October he released his second [[Christmas music|Christmas album]], and ninth studio album, ''[[Slay Belles]]''. The album contains ten original Christmas-themed songs and features collaborations with [[Michelle Visage]], [[Siedah Garrett]], [[Todrick Hall]] and [[Big Freedia]]. The album charted at 21 on the US ''[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]]'' [[Dance/Electronic Albums|Dance]] chart.<ref name=\"billboard.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/369236/rupaul/chart?f=322|title=RuPaul&nbsp;\u2014 Chart history|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>\n\n===2016: ''Gay for Play,'' ''Butch Queen,'' ''All Stars 2''===\nIn January 2016, it was announced RuPaul would present a new game show for [[Logo TV]] called ''[[Gay for Play Game Show Starring RuPaul]]'' which premiered on April 11, 2016 after ''RuPaul's Drag Race''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/logo-gay-for-play-game-show-rupaul-1201684468/|title=Logo Greenlights Two New Series Including RuPaul Game Show, Following Year-Over-Year Growth|author=Elizabeth Wagmeister|work=Variety|date=2016-01-21}}</ref> In February 2016, RuPaul announced his tenth album, ''[[Butch Queen]]''. It was released in March 2016, just prior to the premiere of the [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 8)|eighth season]] of ''RuPaul's Drag Race''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newnownext.com/rupaul-announces-new-album-butch-queen-dropping-march-7/02/2016/|title=Rupaul Announces New Album, \"Butch Queen,\" Dropping March 7!|author=Dan Avery|work=NewNowNext}}</ref> A song from the album, \"U Wear It Well\" was featured in the teaser campaigns for the season and was later officially released as the first single on iTunes in February 2016. The album charted at number 3 on the US ''[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]]'' [[Dance/Electronic Albums|Dance]] chart, marking his highest position on this chart to date (2016?).<ref name=\"billboard.com\"/> \"'Be Someone\" featuring American singer [[Taylor Dayne]] was released as the album's second and final single. Additionally, ''[[Butch Queen|Butch Queen: The Ru-Mixes]]'' was released.\n\nIn July 2016, it was announced that RuPaul was nominated for the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Host for a Reality or Reality-Competition Program]]. He would go on to win the award at the September [[68th Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards|Creative Arts Emmy Awards Ceremony]]. 2016 also saw the release of the single \"Read U Wrote U\" that features rap parts by the ''RuPaul's Drag Race All Stars 2'' finalists [[Roxxxy Andrews]], [[Katya Zamolodchikova]], [[Alaska Thunderfuck]], and [[Detox Icunt]] with production by [[Ellis Miah]].<ref name=\"miah\">{{cite web |title=Read U Wrote U (Ellis Miah Mix) [feat. The Cast of RuPaul's Drag Race All Stars, Season 2] - Single by RuPaul |url=https://itunes.apple.com/ca/album/read-u-wrote-u-ellis-miah-mix-feat-cast-rupauls-drag/1163061808 |website=itunes.apple.com |language=en-ca}}</ref>\n\n===2017\u20132018: ''Remember Me'', ''American'', return to VH1, and ''Essential, Vol. 2''===\nOn January 27, 2017, RuPaul announced that a new album would be released the week after. The album, named ''[[Remember Me: Essential, Vol. 1]]'' was put up for pre-order on February 2 and eventually released the next day. It is a collection of new songs and remakes of classic RuPaul hits that feature new artists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2017/02/06/rupaul-chats-about-reinventing-his-back-catalog-for-a-new-audience/#772ba3d8156d|title=RuPaul Chats About Reinventing His Back Catalog For A New Audience|first=Hugh|last=McIntyre|publisher=}}</ref> Two singles have been released from the album so far: \"Rock It (To The Moon)\" which is a new song loosely based on the lyrics and the melody of \"Hey Booty\" which was released on the ''Starrbooty'' soundtrack in 2007, and an updated version of RuPaul's 1996 hit single \"Snapshot\" from the album ''Foxy Lady''. The album failed to chart on the Dance Albums Chart but managed to debut at number four on the ''Billboard'' Dance Albums Sales Chart in the United States. It also charted at number eleven on the UK Dance Albums Chart, becoming RuPaul's highest charting album on that chart, after ''Realness'' managed to debut and peak at number 13.\n\nOn March 24, 2017, RuPaul released his eleventh studio album, ''[[American (album)|American]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.out.com/music/2017/3/22/rupaul-reclaims-core-american-values-political-new-album|title=RuPaul Reclaims Core 'American' Values With Political New Album|date= March 22, 2017|publisher=}}</ref> Later that same day, the [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 9)|ninth regular season]] of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' debuted on basic cable channel VH1, home of RuPaul's talk show in the 1990s. This marked a move from expanded cable channel Logo TV, which aired all previous seasons of the show. The season 9 premiere featured singer [[Lady Gaga]] as its guest judge and proved a success, with ratings of nearly 1,000,000 viewers, making it the series' most viewed episode. This figure was double LogoTV's season 8 premiere ratings from the year prior, and triple VH1's usual Friday night viewership in that programming timeslot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/03/rupauls-drag-race-ratings-records-1-million-viewers-season-9-premiere-vh1-1202053113/|title='RuPaul's Drag Race' Draws Nearly 1M Viewers In VH1 Debut|first=Denise|last=Petski|date= March 27, 2017|publisher=}}</ref> When the ratings were released, World of Wonder Productions announced they were casting contestants for a tenth season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldofwonder.net/its-time-children-casting-for-rupauls-drag-race-season-10-has-begun/|title=It's Time, Children! Casting for 'RuPaul's Drag Race' Season 10 HAS BEGUN!|date= March 27, 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn June 2, 2017, ''[[Essential, Vol. 2]]'' was put up on pre-order on iTunes. It was released on June 9 and preceded by the single \"Crying on the Dance Floor\" which is a re-recording of the 2010 single \"Main Event\" from the album ''[[Champion (RuPaul album)|Champion]]''. On June 22, 2017, it was announced that RuPaul will receive a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] for his contributions to the television industry.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2017/06/23/entertainment/hollywood-walk-fame-2018/index.html |title=Hollywood Walk of Fame Class of 2018 revealed |last=France |first=Lisa Respers |date= June 23, 2017 |website=CNN |access-date=21 February 2018}}</ref> He was awarded the honor on March 16, 2018, making him the first drag queen to be given such an award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/rupaul-hollywood-walk-of-fame|title=RuPaul Is the First Drag Queen to Get a Star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, it was announced that RuPaul will be releasing his third Christmas album in October 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.out.com/entertainment/2018/8/29/ho-ho-ho-rupaul-releasing-new-christmas-album|title=Ho Ho Ho: RuPaul is Releasing a New Christmas Album|publisher=|date=2018-08-29}}</ref>\n\n===2019\u2013present: ''Drag Race UK'', ''AJ and the Queen'' and further TV shows ===\nIn June 2019, a daytime [[talk show]] titled [[RuPaul (talk show)|''RuPaul'']] premiered, however it was cancelled after a three-week test run, since it was not picked by any [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] TV stations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newnownext.com/rupaul-talk-show/04/2019/|title=RuPaul Gets His Oprah On in First Clip From His New Daytime Talk Show|last=Rudolph|first=Christopher|date=April 2, 2019|website=[[NewNowNext]]|accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"hollywoodrep\"/> He also appeared in [[Taylor Swift]]'s \"[[You Need to Calm Down]]\" music video.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/taylor-swift-parties-with-katy-perry-ellen-more-in-new-you-need-to-calm-down-video-watch/|title=Taylor Swift Parties With Katy Perry, RuPaul, More in New \"You Need to Calm Down\" Video: Watch|last=Yoo|first=Noah|date=June 17, 2019|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|accessdate=June 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2019, the [[RuPaul's Drag Race UK (series 1)|first season]] of ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race UK]]'' was released on [[BBC3]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2019/rpdr-judges|title='Graham Norton and Alan Carr confirmed as celebrity judges for RuPaul's Drag Race UK - series to air on BBC Three in 2019|work=[[BBC]]|access-date=8 December 2019|language=en}}</ref> It was well-received, with ''[[The Guardian]]'' stating that the British version had \"saved\" the franchise.<ref name=\"tg-ukrpdr\">{{cite news |last1=Bromwich |first1=Kathryn |title=Fierce competition: how a Brit makeover saved RuPaul's Drag Race |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2019/nov/22/fierce-competition-how-a-brit-makeover-saved-rupauls-drag-race |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=22 November 2019}}</ref> It was renewed for a second season to be released in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ashurst|first1=Sam |title=RuPaul's Drag Race UK season 2 audition, casting air date, trailer and everything you need to know|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/reality-tv/a30079234/rupauls-drag-race-uk-season-2-audition-casting-air-date-trailer/|website=Digital Spy|accessdate=5 December 2019|date=2 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nRupaul also created and starred in the [[Netflix]] drama-comedy show ''[[AJ and the Queen]]'' as a drag queen touring the country with an unlikely young sidekick, which was released on January 10, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=Shows A-Z - AJ and the Queen on Netflix |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/aj-and-the-queen/listings/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=TheFutonCritic.com}}</ref> On March 6, 2020, Netflix announced that the series had been cancelled.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://money.yahoo.com/aj-queen-cancelled-netflix-163654199.html|title=AJ and the Queen Cancelled at Netflix|date=March 6, 2020|first=Andy|last=Swift|website=money.yahoo.com|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAlso in January 2020, it was announced that RuPaul would host ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' for the first time. He hosted the episode airing on February 8, 2020 with [[Justin Bieber]] as a musical guest.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ew.com/tv/2020/01/21/rupaul-hosting-saturday-night-live/|title=RuPaul to host Saturday Night Live for the first time|date=January 21, 2020|first=Joey|last=Nolfi|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=January 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\n\nRuPaul is considered to be the most commercially successful drag queen in the United States.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite article |title=How RuPaul Became a Leading Icon in the Gay Community |website=Mic.com |date=May 29, 2013 |url=https://mic.com/articles/44947/how-rupaul-became-a-leading-icon-in-the-gay-community#.mjWQkaIfc }}</ref> He has been credited with creating wider exposure for drag queens from [[LGBT culture]] in to [[Mainstream media|mainstream]] society, thanks to his early-career chart success, and later, the successive climb in viewership of ''RuPaul's Drag Race''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adweek.com/tv-video/rupaul-on-moving-to-mainstream-television-and-the-political-nature-of-drag-culture/|title=RuPaul on Moving to Mainstream Television and the 'Political' Nature of Drag Culture|publisher=}}</ref> His talk show ''The RuPaul Show'' was the first ever national talk show to have a drag queen as a host. Along with his partner Michelle Visage, he welcomed an array of high-profile guests such as [[Cher]], [[Lil Kim]], and [[Diana Ross]] over the show's 100-episode span. As well as having a variety of comedy [[skits]], the show was noted for discussing topics such as black empowerment, [[female empowerment]], [[misogyny]], and liberal politics which were otherwise unheard of in 1990s television at the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/artsandculture/article/33452/1/why-rupaul-was-a-cultural-icon-long-before-drag-race|title=Why RuPaul was a cultural icon long before Drag Race|last=Dazed|date= October 25, 2016|publisher=}}</ref> In 1999, RuPaul was awarded the [[GLAAD Vito Russo Award|Vito Russo Award]] at the [[GLAAD Media Award]]s for work in promoting equality in the [[LGBT community]].\n\nRuPaul has also been noted as having a large part in ''RuPaul's Drag Race'''s continuous television success. By pioneering queer representation on television, many believe RuPaul to have essentially revolutionised the portrayal of the [[LGBTQ]]+ community on screen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teenvogue.com/story/how-rupauls-drag-race-led-a-gay-cultural-revolution|title=How 'RuPaul's Drag Race' Led a Gay Cultural Revolution&nbsp;\u2013 and Changed My Life|first=Ryan|last=Houlihan|publisher=}}</ref> He first won an [[Emmy]] for his work on the show in 2016, and one year later the show garnered eight nominations, including [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Reality-Competition Program|Outstanding Reality-Competition Program]] for the first time in its 11-season run, and a second consecutive win for RuPaul in the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Host for a Reality or Reality-Competition Program]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vulture.com/2017/07/rupauls-drag-race-emmy-nomination-finally.html|title=Straight Emmy Voters Finally Discover RuPaul's Drag Race|first=E. Alex|last=Jung|publisher=}}</ref> In 2017, he was included in the annual [[Time 100|''Time'' 100]] list of the most influential people in the world.<ref name=\"time\">{{cite news|url=http://time.com/collection/2017-time-100/4736291/rupaul/|title=RuPaul: The World's 100 Most Influential People|website=Time}}</ref> In 2019 ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' noted RuPaul as \u201ceasily the world's most famous\u201d drag queen.<ref name=\"klein1\"/>\n\n=== Relationship with transgender community ===\nRuPaul has a complex relationship with the transgender community, in part due to differing philosophies: through drag he seeks to mock gender and identity stereotypes, while in his view the trans community takes identity seriously.<ref name=\"Vox-2018\">{{cite news |title=How RuPaul's comments on trans women led to a Drag Race revolt \u2013 and a rare apology |url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2018/3/6/17085244/rupaul-trans-women-drag-queens-interview-controversy |accessdate=September 3, 2018 |work=Vox |quote=To understand why RuPaul has always been resistant to let go of what he finds to be harmless jokes, you have to understand that he built his career on the principle that no one should take themselves or gender particularly seriously. In fact, as he told Vulture, his vision of drag is that it's meant to \"remind culture to not take itself seriously.\" When he gets asked about the trans community's relation to drag, he said, he just gets bored because \"we mock identity. They take identity very seriously.\"}}</ref> ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' has featured a number of contestants who are [[Trans woman|trans women]], some of whom made their identity public while competing on the show, including [[Sonique (drag queen)|Sonique]], [[Carmen Carrera]], [[Jiggly Caliente]], [[Monica Beverly Hillz]], [[Kenya Michaels]] and [[Gia Gunn]].<ref name=\"gia-trans\">{{cite news |last1=Rudolph |first1=Christopher |title=Former \"Drag Race\" Contestant Gia Gunn Comes Out As Trans |url=http://www.newnownext.com/gia-gunn-trans-rupauls-drag-race/03/2017/ |accessdate=September 3, 2018 |work=LOGO News |date= March 31, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"salandra\">{{cite news |last1=Salandra |first1=Adam |title=11 Times \"RuPaul's Drag Race\" Celebrated The Trans Community |url=http://www.newnownext.com/rupauls-drag-race-transgender/04/2017/ |accessdate=September 3, 2018 |work=LOGO News |date= April 29, 2017}}</ref> In 2017 [[Peppermint (drag queen)|Peppermint]] became the first contestant to compete throughout her season as an openly [[transgender woman]].<ref name=\"pep-gsn-2018\">{{cite news |last1=Morgan |first1=Joe |title=Was trans queen Peppermint told to dress 'as a man' on Drag Race? |url=https://www.gaystarnews.com/article/trans-queen-peppermint-told-dress-man-drag-race |accessdate=September 3, 2018 |work=Gay Star News |date=6 March 2018}}</ref> Other non-conforming gender identities expressed by former contestants include [[nonbinary]] ([[Jinkx Monsoon]], [[Adore Delano]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Voss |first1=Brandon |title=Adore Delano Talks New Punk Album 'Whatever', the '27 Club' & Being Nonbinary: 'Gender Isn't a Real Thing' |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/pride/7934257/adore-delano-new-album-whatever-nonbinary-gender-interview |accessdate=24 January 2019 |work=Billboard |date= August 21, 2017}}</ref> [[Aja (entertainer)|Aja]] and [[Valentina (drag queen)|Valentina]]), [[gender fluid]] ([[Courtney Act]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ashenden |first1=Amy |title=What does gender-fluid mean? Courtney Act explains how gender-fluidity set her free |url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2018/04/25/courtney-act-gender-fluid/ |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=PinkNews |date=25 April 2018}}</ref> and [[Kelly Mantle]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Yohannes |first1=Alamin |title=Gender-fluid actor Kelly Mantle makes Oscars history |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbc-out/gender-fluid-actor-kelly-mantle-makes-oscars-history-n694926 |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=NBC News |date=12 December 2016 |language=en}}</ref>) and [[genderqueer]] ([[Violet Chachki]] and [[Sasha Velour]]).<ref name=\"valentina-nb\">{{cite news |last1=Rodriguez |first1=Mathew |title=Valentina Identifies as Nonbinary: \"I'm My Own Gender\" |url=https://www.out.com/entertainment/2019/1/14/valentina-identifies-non-binary-im-my-own-gender |accessdate= January 24, 2019 |work=Out.com |date= January 14, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/sasha_velour/status/830305619886366720|title=Thank so much for asking @glassarmy! For my Velour self \u2013 always she/her (out of drag its even less binary lol...any will do) #genderqueer|last=Velour|first=Sasha|date=February 10, 2017|website=@sasha_velour|access-date=March 19, 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=April 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=May 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 trans activists and former contestants Carmen Carrera and Monica Beverly Hillz criticized the show's use of words such as ''[[tranny]]'' and ''[[shemale]],'' including the main challenge announcement phrase up to season 6, \"You've got she-mail\", which they described as [[Transphobia|transphobic]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Campbell |first1=Nigel |title=Carmen Carrera Clashes w/ RuPaul In 'Tranny' Controversy |url=http://instinctmagazine.com/post/carmen-carrera-clashes-w-rupaul-tranny-controversy |accessdate= September 3, 2018 |work=Instinct |date= May 27, 2014 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"huffpo-ru-maron\">{{cite news |last1=Nichols |first1=JamesMichael |title=RuPaul Responds To Controversy Over The Word 'Tranny' |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com.au/entry/rupaul-responds-tranny_n_5374897 |accessdate= September 3, 2018 |work=Huffington Post |date= May 23, 2014 |language=en-AU}}</ref> [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 6)|That year's season]] also included a \"Female or She-male\" segment which required contestants to guess whether various photographs featured [[cisgender]] \"biological women\" or \"psychological women\" (drag queens), causing further criticism.<ref name=\"slate-2014\">{{cite news |last1=D'Angelo |first1=Rafi |title=RuPaul's Drag Race&nbsp;Crosses the Line with \"Female or Shemale\" |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/outward/2014/03/19/rupaul_s_drag_race_and_transphobia_why_the_shemale_game_was_offensive.html |accessdate= September 3, 2018 |work=Slate |date= March 19, 2014}}</ref> RuPaul and the producers issued a statement promising \"to help spread love, acceptance and understanding\" and Logo TV removed the \"You've got she-mail\" phrase from subsequent broadcasts.<ref name=\"2014-april-response\">{{cite news |last1=Nichols |first1=JamesMichael |title='RuPaul's Drag Race' Producers Respond To Claims Of Transphobia |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com.au/entry/drag-race-transphobia_n_5062692 |accessdate= September 3, 2018 |work=Huffington Post |date= April 1, 2014 |language=en-AU}}</ref> RuPaul criticized those attempting to police his language in bad faith and noted that ''tranny'' referred to [[Transvestism|transvestites]] and drag queens, not just trans women.<ref name=\"advocate-2014-ru-response\">{{cite news |last1=Peeples |first1=Jason |title=RuPaul Further Responds to Transphobic Accusations: \"I've Been a 'Tranny' For 32 Years\" |url=https://www.advocate.com/%5Bprimary-topic-path-raw%5D/2014/05/26/rupaul-further-responds-transphobic-accusations-ive-been-trannye-been-tranny |accessdate= September 3, 2018 |work=The Advocate |date= March 23, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"salon-2014\">{{cite news |last1=D'Addario |first1=Daniel |title=RuPaul's aggressive tirade in defense of the term \"tranny\" |url=https://www.salon.com/2014/05/27/rupauls_aggressive_tirade_in_defense_of_the_term_tranny/ |accessdate= September 3, 2018 |work=Salon |date= May 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 RuPaul gave an interview to ''[[The Guardian]]'' in which he stated that a post-transition trans woman would \"probably not\" be accepted onto the show, noting that at the time of competition Peppermint had not yet had breast implants.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Aitkenhead |first1=Decca |title=RuPaul: 'Drag is a big f-you to male-dominated culture' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/mar/03/rupaul-drag-race-big-f-you-to-male-dominated-culture |accessdate= September 3, 2018 |work=The Guardian |date= March 3, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> After facing criticism on social media and from former contestants for his remarks,<ref name=\"advocate-2014-2018-changes\">{{cite news |last1=Reynolds |first1=Daniel |title=The Meaning of RuPaul's Apology: What Changed From 2014 to 2018? |url=https://www.advocate.com/transgender/2018/3/10/meaning-rupauls-apology-what-changed-2014-2018 |accessdate= September 3, 2018 |date=March 10, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> RuPaul compared trans drag queens who had transitioned to athletes who had taken performance-enhancing drugs.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Duffy |first1=Nick |title=RuPaul compares transgender drag queens to Olympics drug cheats, doubles down on Drag Race 'ban' |url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2018/03/05/rupaul-compares-transgender-drag-queens-to-doping-athletes-doubles-down-on-drag-race-ban/ |accessdate=September 3, 2018 |work=PinkNews |date=5 March 2018}}</ref> He subsequently expressed regret for the hurt caused by his remarks, and that the only screening criteria for contestants were \"charisma, uniqueness, nerve, and talent\".<ref name=\"towle-2018-regret\">{{cite news |last1=Towle |first1=Andy |title=RuPaul Tweets 'Regret' for 'Hurt I Have Caused' to Trans Community for 'Drag Race' Eligibility Remarks |url=http://www.towleroad.com/2018/03/rupaul-transgender/ |accessdate= September 3, 2018 |work=Towleroad Gay News |date= March 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRuPaul is gay. He has been with his husband, Georges LeBar, since 1994, when they met at [[the Limelight]] nightclub in [[LGBT culture in New York City|New York City]].\nThey married in January 2017.<ref>{{cite article |title=RuPaul reveals he married boyfriend in January |website=BBC News |date= March 16, 2017 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-39289862 }}</ref> They have an [[open marriage]], with RuPaul stating he would not want to \"put restraints\" on the person he loves.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Milton |first1=Josh |title=RuPaul discusses his open marriage in rare, candid interview |url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2019/11/26/rupaul-drag-race-open-marriage-relationship-georges-lebar-vanity-fair/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=PinkNews - Gay news, reviews and comment from the world's most read lesbian, gay, bisexual, and trans news service |date=26 November 2019}}</ref> LeBar is a painter<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.georgeslebar.com/|title=Georges LeBar|website=www.georgeslebar.com}}</ref> and runs a {{convert|60,000|acre|m2|adj=on}} ranch in [[Wyoming]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/10/813970591/rupauls-recipe-for-success-love-yourself-and-stay-flexible|title=RuPaul's Recipe For Success? Love Yourself And Stay Flexible|date=March 10, 2020|website=NPR|accessdate=March 10, 2020|quote=\"RuPaul, who splits time between Los Angeles and a 60,000-acre ranch in Wyoming, says one of the secrets to his success is adaptability.\"}}</ref> \n\nHe was criticized by environmentalists after revealing in 2020 that he and his husband lease mineral rights and sell water to oil companies on their ranch and allow [[fracking]], an [[Environmental impact of hydraulic fracturing|environmentally harmful]] practice.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Boyle |first1=Louise |title=RuPaul: Environmental outcry after Drag Race star suggests he allows fracking on ranch |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/environment/ru-paul-fracking-ranch-drag-race-environment-a9407461.html |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Independent |date=17 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> There are at least 35 active wells on the LeBar Ranch according to public maps.<ref>{{cite news |title=RuPaul Has a Fracking Empire on His Wyoming Ranch |url=https://earther.gizmodo.com/rupaul-has-a-fracking-empire-on-his-wyoming-ranch-1842364626 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Earther |publisher=Gizmodo |date=17 March 2020 |language=en-us}}</ref> RuPaul previously held a climate-themed ball on his show to raise environmental awareness, leading to accusations of hypocrisy.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Most Unexpected Revelation From RuPaul\u2019s Recent NPR Interview? He Might Be Fracking |url=https://www.texasmonthly.com/the-culture/is-rupaul-fracking/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Texas Monthly |date=19 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> \n\nRuPaul publicly endorsed the [[Democratic Party (US)|Democratic Party]] nominee [[Hillary Clinton]] in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 U.S. Presidential election]].<ref>{{cite article |title=\"Don't f*ck it up\": RuPaul issues plea ahead of US presidential vote |date=November 7, 2016 |website=PinkNews |url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2016/11/07/dont-fck-it-up-rupaul-issues-plea-ahead-of-us-presidential-vote-video/ }}</ref> He expressed dismay at Clinton's defeat by [[Republican Party (US)|Republican Party]] nominee [[Donald Trump]], stating that \"The America that we have all fought so hard for, the narrative of love and peace and liberty and equality, it feels like it is dead.\"<ref>{{cite article |title=RuPaul \"feels like death\" about Donald Trump's election |website=PinkNews |date=December 15, 2016 |url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2016/12/15/rupaul-feels-like-death-about-donald-trumps-election/ }}</ref>\n\nHe has described doing drag as a \"very, very political\" act because it \"challenges the status quo\" by rejecting fixed identities: \"drag says 'I'm a shapeshifter, I do whatever the hell I want at any given time'.\"<ref>{{cite article |title='RuPaul's Drag Race' Is Leaving TV's Biggest Gay Network&nbsp;\u2013 Now What? |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/rupauls-drag-race-logo-vh1_us_58d1b0bce4b0b22b0d17f9aa?5hxh9fw6vsded0a4i |website=Huffington Post |date= March 23, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nRuPaul has said he has been sober from alcohol and mind-altering substances since 1999, having started smoking [[marijuana]] at age 10 or 11.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sim |first=Bernardo |url=https://screenrant.com/rupauls-drag-race-things-didnt-know-rupaul/ |title=RuPaul\u2019s Drag Race: 10 Things You Didn\u2019t Know About RuPaul |publisher=Screenrant.com |date=2019-09-10 |accessdate=2020-01-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Michael Schulman |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/23/fashion/RuPaul-Drag-Race-television.html |title=For RuPaul, A Second Act with \u2018Drag Race\u2019 - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=2014-02-23 |accessdate=2020-01-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2-yI9PEmTx4 |title=RuPaul Loves Wrestling 'For All The Reasons You Think' |publisher=YouTube |date=2020-01-09 |accessdate=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\n==Other ventures==\n\n===Podcasting===\nThe [[podcast]] ''[[RuPaul: What's the Tee?|RuPaul: What's The Tee? With Michelle Visage]]'' debuted on April 6, 2014. Ru-Paul co-hosts with longtime friend and fellow ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' judge [[Michelle Visage]]. The weekly show features their thoughts on topics including behind-the-scenes of ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]]'', life advice, beauty tips, and conversations with featured guests from the entertainment world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/arts-entertainment/people/2014/04/09/listen-rupaul-debuts-official-podcast-what%E2%80%99s-tee|title=Listen: RuPaul Debuts Official Podcast 'What's the Tee?'|first=Jase|last= Peeples|work=Advocate.com}}</ref><ref>[http://www.rupaulpodcast.com ''RuPaul: What's The Tee? With Michelle Visage''] website.</ref>\n\n===Audiobooks===\nIn 2018, RuPaul was one of the actors who voiced the audiobook ''[[A Day in the Life of Marlon Bundo]]''.<ref name=\"Bundo AV Club\">{{cite news |last=Perkins |first=Dennis |date=March 19, 2018 |title=John Oliver hijacks homophobe Mike Pence's bunny book with a better one in A Day In The Life Of Marlon Bundo |url=https://www.avclub.com/john-oliver-hijacks-homophobe-mike-pences-bunny-book-wi-1823879129 |work=AV Club |location= |access-date=March 19, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n===Drag conventions===\nLaunched through production company [[World of Wonder (company)|World of Wonder]], [[RuPaul's DragCon LA]], is an annual drag-themed convention held in Los Angeles starting in 2015, followed by [[RuPaul's DragCon NYC]] as of 2017 in New York City, which allows members of the public to meet with RuPaul, former ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' contestants and other drag queens.<ref name=\"laweekly-dragcon-2018\">{{cite news |last1=Lecaro |first1=Lina |title=RuPaul's DragCon Returns to Wow L.A. |url=https://www.laweekly.com/arts/rupauls-dragcon-returns-to-wow-la-9409656 |accessdate= September 3, 2018 |work=L.A. Weekly |date=3 May 2018}}</ref> The conventions feature performances, meet-and-greet booths, merchandise sales and panel discussions.<ref name=\"hobro-dragcon-2018\">{{cite news |last1=Hobro |first1=Marie E. |title=RuPaul's DragCon LA returns for its fourth year |url=http://www.latimes.com/visuals/photography/la-me-drag-con-unfurled-gallery-20180521-story.html |accessdate=September 3, 2018 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=May 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|RuPaul discography}}\n\n;Studio albums\n* ''[[Supermodel of the World]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Foxy Lady (RuPaul album)|Foxy Lady]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[Ho Ho Ho (album)|Ho Ho Ho]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[Red Hot (album)|Red Hot]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Champion (RuPaul album)|Champion]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Glamazon (album)|Glamazon]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Born Naked]]'' (2014)\n* ''